lets look at what data were actually marked as outliers. Outliers are marked red and the plots are sorted from most outliers to fewest. The blue dots are before any transformation has been done (not important here, but important later), and the green rug plot is after transformation

In [7]:
def get_outliers(cleaned, orig, variables):
    outliers = cleaned[variables].isnull() - orig[variables].isnull()
    return outliers

def plot_outliers(cleaned, orig, variables):
    outliers = get_outliers(cleaned, orig, variables)
    num_with_outliers = np.sum(outliers.mean()>0)
    outliers = outliers.loc[:,outliers.mean()>0]
    f, axes = plt.subplots(ceil(num_with_outliers/3), 3, figsize=(12,num_with_outliers))
    axes = f.get_axes()
    i=0
    variables=outliers.mean().sort_values().index[::-1]
    for name, var in orig[variables].iteritems():
        ax = axes[i]
        outlier = outliers[name]
        var_kept = var[~outlier]
        var_outliers = var[outlier]
        sns.stripplot(var_kept, ax=ax, size=4, alpha=.8)
        sns.stripplot(var_outliers, color='r', ax=ax, size=3)
        sns.rugplot(cleaned[name], ax=ax, alpha=.5, color='g')
        ax.set_title('\n'.join(name.split('.')))
        ax.set_xlabel('')
        ax.text(.3, .8, 'Outlier %%: %s' % format_num(outlier.mean()), 
                transform=ax.transAxes, fontsize=12)
        i+=1
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=.5, hspace=.5)
    
plot_outliers(outliers_removed, selected_variables, variables_removed)

Different cleaning approaches¶

Procedure 1 (Skew is all!)¶

  • remove outliers if doing so removes skew
  • transform variables that are skewed.
  • if variables are still skewed, drop outliers
  • if variables are still skewed, drop them
In [8]:

Proceudre 4, not run¶

  • remove outliers if doing so removes skew
  • transform variables that are skewed.
  • drop variables if they would still be skewed after following outliers removal
  • remove outliers from all variables except the first group
  • remove outliers from transformed variables that need it.

Let's compare both of these approaches now¶

Skew¶

All approaches remove skew, obviously. Every kept variable at the end is within our skew thresholds

Procedure 1¶

Now we are going to look at outlier removal. For the first procedure there are two places where outliers are removed. Outliers are removed to remove skew and outliers are removed from failed transformed data if doing so makes them unskewed enough. 18 variables had outliers removed using the first procedure, and a further 5 were transformed after being transformed. We will just look at the 18, actually the same as above

In [12]:
def remove_suffix(df):
    df.columns = ['.'.join(i.split('.')[:-1]) if 'logTr' in i else i for i in df.columns]
In [13]:
tmp = selected_variables_clean.copy()
remove_suffix(tmp)
variables = list(set(variables_removed) & set(tmp.columns))

# here are the 18 variables
outliers = get_outliers(tmp, selected_variables, variables)
sns.boxplot(outliers.mean()); plt.xlabel('Percent outliers removed', fontsize=20)
plt.title('% Outliers Removed across tasks', fontsize=20)
plot_outliers(tmp, selected_variables, variables)

Procedure 2¶

For the second procedure there are also two places where outliers are removed. Outliers are removed to remove skew. If there are still skewed variables, these are transformed. Then all variables have outliers removed.

Procedure 3¶

For the third procedure there is one place where outliers are removed. Skewed variables are transformed. All variables have outliers removed. The blue distribution here now represents the transformed distribution.

There is one outlier case which I have dug into after these plots.

In [15]:

/media/Data/Ian/miniconda/envs/SRO/lib/python3.5/site-packages/pandas/core/computation/expressions.py:180: UserWarning: evaluating in Python space because the '-' operator is not supported by numexpr for the bool dtype, use '^' instead
  .format(op=op_str, alt_op=unsupported[op_str]))

One variable seemed odd. It was the shift task model-beta. It seems that a decent number of subjects have a beta value=1 (the starting value). At the same time, the variable is skewed, so it is transformed, making all of those 1's 0's. Not sure what to do here.

Procedure 2 deals with this by removing the right outliers first. Then it is not skewed and doesn't need to be trasnformed. We can imagine doing a hybrid of procedure 2 and 3, where the first outlier detection is for huge anomolies, but now we are just making procedures to fit to one variable (still may not be a bad idea).

Evaluate all distributions¶

# look clean and imputed data clean = get_behav_data(file = 'meaningful_variables_clean.csv') imputed = get_behav_data(file = 'meaningful_variables_imputed.csv') clean_melted=clean.melt().assign(stage='clean') impute_melted=imputed.melt().assign(stage='imputed') final = pd.concat([clean_melted, impute_melted]) # remove missing values final = final.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan) final.dropna(inplace=True)%matplotlib inline n_rows=clean.shape[1] f, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, 2, figsize=(7, n_rows*3)) for row, name in enumerate(sorted(final.variable.unique())): for col, stage in enumerate(['clean','imputed']): subset = final.query('variable == "%s" and stage == "%s"' % (name, stage)) if len(subset) > 0: axes[row][col].hist(subset['value'], bins=20) axes[row][0].set_ylabel(('\n').join(name.split('.')), fontsize=15, rotation=0, labelpad=100) axes[row][col].set_title(str(stage)) axes[row][col].text(.75,.6,format_num(subset.value.skew()), fontsize=15, color='black', transform = axes[row][col].transAxes) axes[row][col].text(.75,.8,format_num(float(medcouple(subset.value))), fontsize=15, color='red', transform = axes[row][col].transAxes)f.savefig('/home/ian/tmp/distributions_outlier.pdf', bbox_inches='tight')
